<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1905-08-14T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1905-08-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="988" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d988">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to Minister <persName type="to">Leishman</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1905-08-14"><hi rend="italic">August 14,
                                1905</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 877.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I inclose herewith for your information a
                            copy of a letter from Mr. J. B. Hammond,<note n="a" xml:id="d988fna">Not
                                printed.</note> in regard to 19 typewriting machines shipped by him
                            to Messrs. Bond, Seller &amp; Co., of Constantinople, Turkey, which have
                            been detained in the custom-house.</p>
                        <pb facs="1004" n="884" xml:id="pg_884"/>
                        <p>You are requested to give this matter your attention and advise the
                            Department of the result.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Alvey A. Adee.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>